{{Infobox hieroglyphs
|NAME = <hiero>F31-s-N29 t*t:N25</hiero>
|NAME-EXPLANATION = Mesqet<br /> ''Msqt''
}}

'''Mesqet''' (in other {{ill|Publication|de|Publikation|12=draft}}s, in some cases also '''Mesket''') designates in {{ill|Egyptian mythology|de|Ägyptische Mythologie|lt=Egyptian mythology|lt_ja=ägyptischen Mythologie|12=draft}} and {{ill|Astronomy in Ancient Egypt|de|Astronomie im Alten Ägypten|lt=Astronomy in Ancient Egypt|lt_ja=Astronomie|12=draft}} the celestial region just above the {{ill|horizon|de|Horizont|12=draft}} and specifically refers, in contrast to {{ill|Qenqenet|de|Qenqenet|12=draft}}, to the initial areas of the {{ill|Duat|de|Duat|12=draft}}.

== Background ==
[[File:Mock_mirage_of_the_setting_sun.jpg|alt=Mesqet Zone: Sunrise just above the horizon|thumb]]

The Mesqet is the place where {{ill|Ra|de|Re (ägyptische Mythologie)|lt=Ra|lt_ja=Re|12=draft}}, {{ill|Horus|de|Horus|12=draft}} and the {{ill|Baktiu|de|Dekan-Stern|lt=Decan stars|lt_ja=Dekan-Sterne|pt|12=draft}} are situated shortly after their birth, before they fully appear above the horizon. Mesqet is, in mythological terms, "the place after birth, before the final magnitude is reached" ({{ill|mythology|de|Mythologie|lt=mythological|lt_ja=mythologisch|12=draft}}).

The location of Mesqet was long disputed among {{ill|Egyptologists|de|Ägyptologe|12=draft}}, since this area is attested in many texts as "a region in the sky and in the Duat." Mesqet already plays a significant role especially in the {{ill|Pyramid Texts|de|Pyramidentexte|12=draft}}. For example, it was believed by {{ill|Kurt Sethe|de|Kurt Sethe|12=draft}},<ref>Kurt Sethe: ''Die altägyptischen Pyramidentexte. Nach den Papierabdrücken und Photographien des Berliner Museums.'' Volume 1: ''Text. – Hälfte 1. Spruch 1 – 468 (Pyr. 1 – 905).'' 3rd reprint of the Hinrichs edition, Leipzig 1908; Olms, Hildesheim 2001, ISBN 3-487-02593-0, p. 315.</ref> {{ill|Arielle Kozloff|de|Arielle Kozloff|12=draft}},<ref>Arielle Kozloff et al.: ''Egypt’s dazzling sun – Amenhotep III and his world.'' Cleveland Museum of Art in cooperation with Indiana University Press, Cleveland 1992, ISBN 0-940717-16-6, pp. 336–337.</ref> and {{ill|Ronald Wells|de|Ronald Wells|12=draft}},<ref>Ronald Wells: ''The Mythology of Nut and the Birth of Ra.'' In {{ill|Studies in Ancient Egyptian Culture|de|Studien zur Altägyptischen Kultur|12=draft}}, No. 19, 1992, pp. 305–321.</ref> that it might be the {{ill|Milky Way|de|Milchstraße|12=draft}}. Subsequent investigations of other texts, however, could no longer maintain this suggestion, as the other evidence clearly referred to a "transit region of the {{ill|sky (planetary)|de|Himmel (planetär)|lt=sky|lt_ja=Himmels|12=draft}} and the {{ill|star|de|Stern|lt=stars|lt_ja=Sterne|12=draft}}."

After extensive studies by {{ill|Harco Willems|de|Harco Willems|12=draft}},<ref>Harco Willems: ''The coffin of Heqata (Cairo JdE 36418): A case study of Egyptian funerary culture of the Early Middle Kingdom.'' Peeters, Leuven 1996, ISBN 90-6831-769-5, pp. 262–270.</ref> {{ill|Rolf Krauss|de|Rolf Krauss|12=draft}},<ref>Rolf Krauss: ''Astronomical Concepts and Afterlife Beliefs in the Pyramid Texts.'' Harrassowitz, Wiesbaden 1997, ISBN 3-447-03979-5, pp. 254–255.</ref> and {{ill|Arno Egberts|de|Arno Egberts|12=draft}},<ref>Arno Egberts: ''In quest of meaning: A study of the ancient Egyptian rites of consecrating the meret chests and driving the calves.'' Nederlands Institut voor het Nabije Oosten, Leiden 1995, ISBN 90-6258-208-7, pp. 292–293.</ref> the area was narrowed down to the locations of the {{ill|sunrise|de|Sonnenaufgang|12=draft}}. With the results of the investigations of the {{ill|Papyrus|de|Papyrus|12=draft}} {{ill|pBM 47.218.50|de|pBM 47.218.50|12=draft}} and the related subject of the Mesqet sanctuaries ({{ill|Mesqet sanctuaries|de|Mesqet-Heiligtümer|12=draft}}),<ref>Jean-Claude Goyon: ''Confirmation du pouvoir royal au nouvel an: Brooklyn Museum papyrus 47.218.50'' (= ''Bibliothèque d'étude.'' Volume 52). Institut Francais d'Archéologie Orientale, Cairo 1972, pp. 93–94.</ref> it quickly became clear that these newer assumptions correspond with the mention in the Brooklyn Papyrus, which explicitly names only the cardinal directions east and west. Finally, the revision of the {{ill|Book of Nut|de|Nutbuch|12=draft}} confirmed the precise allocation to the regions of the exit gates of the Duat, which are located just above the horizon.

